\begin{aligned} 81^{3^{3^3}} &\equiv 0 \pmod{4}, \\ 81^{3^{3^3}} &\equiv 81 \pmod{125}. \end{aligned}
\] The first congruence tells us that $81^{3^{3^3}}$ is divisible by 4, so it must be divisible by 100. The second congruence tells us that $81^{3^{3^3}}$ leaves a remainder of 81 when divided by 125. Therefore, $81^{3^{3^3}}$ leaves a remainder of $\boxed{81}$ when divided by 1000.

We want to find an integer $x$ such that $27x\equiv 1\pmod{28}$. We can solve this equation by using the Extended Euclidean Algorithm.

First, we find the greatest common divisor (GCD) of 27 and 28 using the Euclidean Algorithm:
\begin{align*}
28 &= 1(27) + 1 \\
27 &= 27(1) + 0
\end{align*}
The GCD of 27 and 28 is 1.

Next, we use the Extended Euclidean Algorithm to find integers $x$ and $y$ such that $27x + 28y = 1$. We start with the last step of the Euclidean Algorithm:
\begin{align*}
1 &= 28(-1) + 27(1) \\
